{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458162,"nonce":"II/hdNMo7NcSgahlUf1COHZCdsw=","title":"Part 2 analysis: plant perturbation responses with SISU","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** The central test of Part 2: does SISU enable the network to modulate its robustness to environmental perturbations? We expect networks trained with adversarial perturbations to show SISU-dependent differences in curl field compensation, trajectory straightness, and force profiles.\n\n**Approach:** Same curl field paradigm as Part 1, now crossed with SISU levels. Computes aligned trajectories (by SISU and by training std), profiles, and comprehensive kinematic/kinetic measures. Includes PCA on hidden states aggregated over pert amp and SISU, plus tangling computation in PC space. Jacobian analysis infrastructure is present but commented out (memory constraints).\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part2/plant_perts.py`. Two versions exist (the main one has tangling enabled; there is a near-duplicate without it). Rich measure set including lateral distance, force measures, and endpoint error.\n\n**References:** Shadmehr \u0026 Mussa-Ivaldi (1994) for curl fields; Russo et al. (2018) for tangling.","files":null}]}